{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480878"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:53:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:53:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"120"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/120"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.45,0.29,0.11,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"120"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94343"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/120"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"120"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77408"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"186"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"5868"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3797"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32489"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44858"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94343"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man, an accountant, presents to his General Practitioner with muscle weakness and sensory loss in his upper extremities that has progressed over the past year. He had first noticed this when he did not feel a burn on his hand when cooking. His medical history is significant for involvement in a motor vehicle accident seven years ago in which he sustained a whiplash cervical spine injury. He takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological assessment of the upper limbs shows moderate wasting of the small hand muscles and impaired pain and temperature sensation in the bilateral upper extremities. Light touch, vibration, and position senses are all intact. His neck range of movement is full and pain free.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intervertebral disc prolapse","Syringomyelia","Cervical spondylosis","Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis","Multiple sclerosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s upper extremity sensory deficits and weakness are best explained by \u003Cstrong\u003Esyringomyelia\u003C/strong\u003E, a disease process in which CSF drainage from the central canal of the spinal cord is disrupted, leading to a fluid filled cavity (syrinx) that compresses surrounding neural tissue (Image). Damage most often involves the crossing fibres of the spinothalamic tract (pain and temperature) and upper extremity motor fibres, due to their medial locations within the corticospinal tract. The loss of pain and temperature is indication the \u201ccompression\u201d is from within the spinal cord, not external to the cord. Classically described in a cape over the shoulder distribution. Syringomyelia most commonly arises in the setting of Chiari malformation (\u0026gt;70%), post-traumatic, post-inflammatory, or post-surgical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome 3-4% of spinal cord injury (SCI) patients go on to develop symptomatic syringomyelia. In cases of syringomyelia caused by SCI, the cervical level of the cord is most often involved. Symptoms may develop months or years after the initial injury, and progression is gradual. Classically, the injury is a motor vehicle accident with whiplash. It is estimated that about 25% of patients suffering a spinal injury will have a syrinx and between 30-50% will have some degree of cystic change within the spinal cord. Characteristic physical exam findings include decreased strength and diminished pain and temperature sensation affecting the arms/hands or having a cape-like distribution, with preservation of dorsal column function (light touch, vibration, position sense).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe symptoms and signs displayed in this case are suggestive of a localised symmetrical process, thus making \u003Cstrong\u003Emultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E less likely. Patients with \u003Cstrong\u003Eamyotrophic lateral sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E manifest muscular weakness and not sensory deficits. \u003Cstrong\u003ECervical spondylosis\u003C/strong\u003E is usually associated neck problems, including difficulty turning the head or bending the neck. Patients with a \u003Cstrong\u003Eprolapsed intervertebral disc\u003C/strong\u003E may have compressive symptoms but in addition, they usually have pain in the back in the region of the prolapse.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Characteristic findings in syringomyelia include decreased strength and diminished pain and temperature sensation affecting the arms/hands, with preservation of dorsal column function"],"references":["Brodbelt AR, Stoodley MA. Post-traumatic syringomyelia: A review. J Clin Neuro. 2003;10:401-08. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12852875/","Handbook of Neurosurgery. Greenberg (ed), 9th edition, 2019. Thieme. ISBN 9781684201372."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77408"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"120"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"2173"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"2173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/2173"},"attributes":{"mimeTyp